<section xml:id="section-activity-clo1">
  <title>Activity for CLO-1</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo1-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the cartesian plane and why is it important?      
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The cartesian plane is a way of connecting algebra and
          geometry by assigning coordinates to geometric point.
          Coordinates are pairs of number which specify location with
          respect to axes. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The cartesian plane is important because it makes the
          connection between algebra and geometry. Geometric problems
          can be solved algebraically using the coordinates, and
          algebraic problems can be interpreted geometrically by
          treating their variables as cartesian coordinates. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is <m>\RR^2</m>? Similarly, whare are <m>\RR^3</m> and
          <m>\RR^n</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\RR^2</m> is notation for the cartesian plane. The
          notation comes from the fact that each axis is like a copy
          of the real numbers, and there are two axes. Similarly,
          <m>\RR^3</m> is notation for catersian space, where there
          are three axes. Even though it is not visualizable, in
          principle we can make a version of cartesian coordinates
          with any number of axes. This is called <m>\RR^n</m>, where
          <m>n</m> can be any positive integer. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a locus? Why is it an important definition in
          analytic geometry?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A locus is the shape in cartesian space defined by an
          equation of the coordinates. It is the main way that algebra
          (and equation) is connected to geometry (shapes), which is
          the fundamentally amazing thing about analytic geometry. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a linear equation in two variables? How is it
          interpreted geometrically?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A linear equation is an equation of the following form (or
          various possible re-arrangements of the equation). 
          <md>
            ax + by + c = 0 
          <md>
          In this, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are variables and <m>a<m>,
          <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are the constant. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The locus of a linear equation is a line. All straight lines
          in the plane correspond to linear equations. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What information is needed to determine the equation of a
          line? 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can determine the equation of a line from three different
          set of information.
          <ul>
            <li>
              If I have the slope and the <m>y</m>-intercept, then I
              can directly put these into the slope-intercept form of
              the equation.
            </li>
            <li>
              If I have a point and a slope, I can put the slope into
              the slope-intercept form of the line and then use the
              point to calculate the intercept. 
            </li>
            <li>
              If I have two points, I can use the two points to
              calculate the slope and then use either point, along
              with the sloipe, to calculate the intercept. 
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the advantages and disadvantages of the
          slope-intercept form of the equation of a line. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The slope-intercept form of the equation of a line has
          several advantages. It is standard and familiar, so easily
          recognized. It isolate the <m>y</m> variable, so it
          resemples the setup for the graph of a function. It is based
          on slope and intercept, which are two easily observed
          geometric facts about a line. Finally, it is easy to
          calcualte and work with algebraiccaly. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The main distadvantage is that the slope-intercept form
          cannot represent vertical lines, since they have no slope. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-equations-of-lines">
    <title>Calculate Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line through the point <m>(3,2)</m>
          with slope 5.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since the slope of the line is 5, using the slope intercept
          form, the equation of the line must be <m>y = 5x + b</m>.
          The only remaining unknown in this expression is the
          intercept <m>b</m>. I can solve for this <m>b</m> by
          inserting the point into the equation.
          <md>
            y = 5x + b \implies 2 = 5(3) + b \implies b = 2 - 15 = -13
          </md>
          Therefore, the equation of the line is <m>y = 5x-13</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line through the point
          <m>(-2,-5)</m> with slope <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since the slope of the line is <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>, using
          the slope intercept form, the equation of the line must be
          <m>y = \frac{1}{3}x + b</m>. The only remaining unknown in
          this expression is the intercept <m>b</m>. I can solve for
          this <m>b</m> by inserting the point into the equation.
          <md>
            -5 = \frac{1}{3}(-2) + b \implies -5 = \frac{-2}{3} + b
            \implies b = -5 + \frac{2}{3} = \frac{-13}{3} 
          </md>
          Therefore, the equation of the line is <m>y =
          \frac{1}{3}x-\frac{13}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line through the point
          <m>(\pi,1)</m> with slope <m>\frac{-1}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since the slope of the line is <m>\frac{-1}{2}</m>, using
          the slope intercept form, the equation of the line must be
          <m>y = \frac{-1}{2}x + b</m>. The only remaining unknown in
          this expression is the intercept <m>b</m>. I can solve for
          this <m>b</m> by inserting the point into the equation.
          <md>
            y = \frac{-1}{2} x + b \implies 1 = \frac{-1}{2} \pi + b
            \implies b = 1 + \frac{\pi}{2} 
          </md>
          Therefore, the equation of the line is <m>y = \frac{-1}{2}x
          + 1 + \frac{\pi}{2}</m>. I might wonder if there is an easier
          way to write this <m>b</m> value. I could express it as a
          decimal: it is approximately 2.57. However, that's less
          precise than simply writing <m>1 + \frac{\pi}{2}</m>, so I
          prefer to write it this way. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line through the points
          <m>(0,4)</m> and <m>(2,2)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need to calculate the slope first: this is calculated as
          the difference in the <m>y</m> coordinates divided by the
          difference in the <m>x</m> coordinates (rise over run). 
          <md>
            m = \frac{4-2}{0-2} = \frac{2}{-2} = -1 
          </md>
          When I have the slope, I can use the slope intercept form,
          so the equation of the line will be <m>y = (-1)x + b</m>.
          Then I can use either of the points in this equation to
          solve for <m>b</m>. (Either point should give the same
          intercept; if they don't, I've made an error somewhere). 
          <md>
            y = -x + b \implies 4 = -0 + b \implies b = 4 
          </md>
          The equation of the line is <m>y = -x + 4</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line through the points
          <m>(-2,6)</m> and <m>(3,2)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need to calculate the slope first: this is calculated as
          the difference in the <m>y</m> coordinates divided by the
          difference in the <m>x</m> coordinates (rise over run).
          <md>
            m = \frac{6-2}{(-2)-3} = \frac{4}{-5} = \frac{-4}{5} 
          </md>
          When I have the slope, I can use the slope intercept form,
          so the equation of the line will be <m>y = \frac{-4}{5}x +
          b</m>. Then I can use either of the points in this
          equation to solve for <m>b</m>. (Either point should give
          the same intercept; if they don't, I've made an error
          somewhere).
          <md>
            y = \frac{-4}{5}x + b \implies 2 = \frac{-4}{5} (3) + b
            \implies 2 = \frac{-12}{5} + b \implies b = 2 +
            \frac{12}{5} = \frac{22}{5}
          </md>
          The equation of the line is <m>y = \frac{-4}{5}x +
          \frac{22}{5}</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line through the points
          <m>(\sqrt{2},3)</m> and <m>(2\sqrt{2},4)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need to calculate the slope first: this is calculated as
          the difference in the <m>y</m> coordinates divided by the
          difference in the <m>x</m> coordinates (rise over run).
          <md>
            m = \frac{4-3}{2\sqrt{2} - \sqrt{2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
          </md>
          When I have the slope, I can use the slope intercept form,
          so the equation of the line will be <m>y =
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} x + b</m>.
          Then I can use either of the points in this equation to
          solve for <m>b</m>. (Either point should give the same
          intercept; if they don't, I've made an error somewhere). 
          <md>
            y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} x + b \implies 3 =
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} (\sqrt{2}) + b \implies 3 = 1 + b
            \implies b = 3 - 1 = 2
          </md>
          The equation of the line is <m>y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x +
          2</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
